latestPosts.caption:
Some places don’t whisper—they roar.
Nanemachi Waterfall isn’t just a destination, it’s a monsoon beast hidden deep in Maharashtra’s lush wilds. The sound of water crashing down, the jungle echoing back—it’s like stepping into a place untouched by time. No crowds, no noise—just raw nature in full power.

The trek? Wet, wild, and absolutely worth it. Every slippery rock and narrow trail leads you to something unreal. You don’t just see this waterfall—you feel it in your bones. This is the kind of place that makes you fall in love with the road, with rain, with being alive.

This one’s for the real explorers—the offbeat travel junkies, the monsoon chasers, the ones who prefer waterfalls over Wi-Fi. Captured it all: the roar, the mist, the moment your breath catches at first sight.

If you’re planning your next hidden getaway, this is it.
Weekend escape. Road trip goal. Nature therapy.
Call it what you want—just don’t miss it.

Turn your screen volume up. Let the visuals hit.
This is Nanemachi—wild, free, unforgettable.
Watch till the end.

Shot on @djiindia.official @djiglobal Mavic 3 Pro

⚠️ Please don’t visit any waterfall during heavy rains. Sudden water surges can turn serene streams into dangerous torrents. Your safety is more important than a selfie.

Hidden in the heart of Malshej Ghat, Kalu Waterfall is Maharashtra’s tallest waterfall, thundering down from a staggering 1200 feet. This five-tiered beauty comes alive during the monsoon, turning the Sahyadris into a misty, green wonderland. 🌧️💚

The Kalu Waterfall trek begins at Khireshwar village and is a moderately challenging trail cutting through forests, rocky ridges, and flowing streams. If you’re searching for offbeat trekking spots near Mumbai or a hidden monsoon destination in Maharashtra, this one’s for you.

Fed by the mighty Harishchandragad mountains, Kalu is raw, wild, and cinematic—perfect for nature lovers, drone shots, and those who love chasing waterfalls. 🌿🌊

🗓️ Best time to visit: July to October.
🎒 Carry good trekking shoes, waterproof covers, and plenty of hydration.

So if you’re looking to escape the ordinary and witness nature’s untamed side, Kalu Waterfall is your next monsoon calling.

Doodhpathri – a name that sounds like a dream, and trust me, it feels exactly like one. Tucked away just a couple of hours from Srinagar, this place isn’t just another stop in Kashmir – it’s where you actually feel the magic of the valley. Wide-open meadows stretch endlessly under a sky that keeps changing colors, and a cold river cuts through like silver thread. If you’re a drone lover, this is a canvas you’ll never forget. The textures from above – pine forests, streams, scattered shepherd huts – they all come together like a painting in motion. Every frame feels like a new story waiting to be told.

As a photographer, I didn’t need to search for moments – they found me. Sunlight breaking through clouds, horses running wild in the wind, a child waving from a wooden fence – it’s raw, it’s real. Doodhpathri doesn’t try too hard to impress. It’s quiet, unpolished, and that’s where its beauty lies. You don’t just visit this place; you feel it deep inside.

If you ever find yourself in Kashmir, don’t skip this. Pack your gadgets , keep your batteries warm, and just let this place surprise you. It surely did that for me.

latestPosts.caption:
All I want is simple. You beside me — not in grand gestures or loud declarations, but in the quiet magic of shared glances and unspoken understanding. The monsoon above, its scent earthy and electric, like nature breathing poetry into the sky. The rain doesn’t ask for shelter; it dances wildly on the windshield, on our skin, like it knows we were meant to move, to feel, to live. And a road that never ends — stretching endlessly ahead, untamed and free, like the love we carry that doesn’t need to be explained.

No maps. No plans. Just miles of wet asphalt gleaming under stormy skies, the hum of the engine syncing with our heartbeats. Your fingers in mine, laughter rising above the roar of rain — this is wanderlust in its purest form. A monsoon road trip, made not for the destination but for the moments in between.

This isn’t a vacation; it’s a feeling. A cinematic escape. Soulful travel. A journey of raw connection and romantic adventure. Let the world rush by — all I want is you, this rain, and a road that forgets where it ends.

Because somewhere between the raindrops and the rolling wheels, I find home.

( Maharashtra, Monsoon, Western Ghats, Sahyadri, Road Trip, Travel Reels)

Raw Vlog: Nanemachi Waterfall In Maharashtra.

Nanemachi Waterfall is one of those places that feels like a dream. Hidden deep in the forests of Maharashtra, it’s perfect for a peaceful weekend getaway. The trek through the greenery, the sound of water falling from the rocks, and the fresh air make it a must-visit travel destination. If you love nature, road trips, or just exploring new places, this spot won’t disappoint. It’s great for monsoon travel and perfect for travel photography too. Nanemachi is not just a waterfall—it’s an experience every travel lover should have on their journey through India’s offbeat locations.

(Monsoon, Maharashtra, Sahyadri, western ghats, waterfall , pune, mumbai, india travel )

Flying isn’t just for birds. When you hold an FPV drone in your hands, you touch the sky in your own way. Every turn, every dive, every flip gives a fresh perspective of the world below. Roads look smaller, and all you feel above is freedom. When the drone flies, it’s not just the machine — your heart soars too. This flight isn’t just about visuals, it’s a feeling — something you live through every frame. Flying FPV means staying grounded, yet living in the skies. Every flight is a story. Every view, a kind of high you can’t explain.

latestPosts.caption:
12-Day Maharashtra Monsoon Road Trip Itinerary

Day 1:
Start early from Pune or Mumbai and drive to the Western Ghats near Mulshi or Tamhini. Visit Nanemachi Waterfall after a 3–4 km walk, then drive to see Saatsada Waterfall. You may also visit Valan Kund, which is just a 30-minute drive away. Stay overnight in Tamhini or Kolad.

Day 2:
After breakfast, hike 8 km one way to Devkund Waterfall. The round-trip walk takes about 3–4 hours.

Day 3:
Visit Kumbe Waterfall in the morning. In the afternoon, explore Raigad Fort before returning to your hotel.

Day 4:
Go on a jungle trek in Andarban. In the evening, drive to Lonavala for the night.

Day 5:
Spend the day visiting a fort. Choose either Korigad Fort or Visapur Fort for great views and history.

Day 6:
Relax in Lonavala or enjoy some adventure activities at Della Resort.

Day 7:
Drive to Matheran, a special hill station where vehicles are not allowed. Stay overnight at a nearby resort.

Day 8:
Head to Malshej Ghat to enjoy the beautiful scenery of the Western Ghats.

Day 9:
Trek to Kalu Waterfall and spend some time enjoying the falls.

Day 10:
Visit the reverse waterfall at Naneghat—a waterfall where the water appears to flow upward—and then return to Malshej.

Day 11:
Choose between trekking the Adarai Jungle Trail or hiking to Harishchandragad for more adventure and views.

Day 12:
Drive back to Pune or Mumbai. Although 12 days is not enough to see everything, this trip shows you the best of Maharashtra in the monsoon season.

Enjoy your road trip and the beautiful sights of Maharashtra during the monsoon!

Shot this in near darkness, using just the car’s headlights to light myself up. 

Shot on @sonyalpha A7M4 

The sun had just dipped below the horizon, leaving behind a beautiful afterglow in the sky — those last few minutes of color before night takes over. Sometimes, you have to get creative with what you have. No fancy lights, just a little planning, timing, and a parked car facing the right way. Low light can be challenging, but it also adds magic when you work with it. Try this next time — use headlights, frame it right, and let the dusk do the rest.

(Low light photography, Sony Alpha, photography tips, camera, travel photographer, shot on sony )

Ever seen a waterfall wash your car? Welcome to the famous “Car Wash Waterfall” at Malshej Ghat, Maharashtra! During the monsoon, this natural wonder spills directly onto the road, giving every passing vehicle a surprise shower. It’s not just fun but breathtaking too—with misty hills, lush greenery, and the roar of falling water all around. Sometimes, strong winds even push the water back up, making it look like a reverse waterfall. It’s one of nature’s coolest magic tricks and a must-see on a rainy day road trip. Just drive slow, enjoy the moment, and let nature take over.

( Malshej Ghat, Monsoon Maharashtra , Car Wash waterfall, western ghat, Sahyadri, waterfall )

POV: Just another unnamed monsoon waterfall in Maharashtra.
No name. No crowd. Just water rushing down a cliff like it’s in a hurry to meet the earth. You didn’t plan to find it — it just showed up, somewhere between the turns and the mist. That’s the thing about Maharashtra in the monsoon… waterfalls pop up like wildflowers. Some roar, some whisper, all of them alive for a short while. This one won’t make it to postcards or guidebooks, but it’ll stay with you — in the sound, the smell of wet soil, and that quiet moment when you paused to take it all in.

( monsoon, Maharashtra, Pune , Mumbai, Western Ghats, Sahyadri , waterfall, india travel reels)
